# 1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)

# 🔹 What are Fundamental Rights?

Fundamental Rights are:

👉 Basic rights guaranteed to citizens for their development and freedom.

Mentioned in:

### Part III

### Articles 12–35

📌 Called:

### “Magna Carta of India”

---

# 🔵 Importance of Fundamental Rights

They:

* Protect liberty
* Prevent misuse of power
* Ensure equality
* Protect democracy

📌 Enforceable by courts.

---

# 🔹 Types of Fundamental Rights

| Right                         | Articles |
| ----------------------------- | -------- |
| Right to Equality             | 14–18    |
| Right to Freedom              | 19–22    |
| Right against Exploitation    | 23–24    |
| Right to Freedom of Religion  | 25–28    |
| Cultural & Educational Rights | 29–30    |
| Constitutional Remedies       | 32       |

---

# 🔴 Right to Equality (Articles 14–18)

## Article 14

### Equality before law & equal protection of laws.

📌 Rule of Law concept.

---

## Article 15

Prohibits discrimination on basis of:

* Religion
* Race
* Caste
* Sex
* Place of birth

---

## Article 16

Equality of opportunity in public employment.

---

## Article 17

Abolition of untouchability.

📌 Very important social justice provision.

---

## Article 18

Abolition of titles.

Exceptions:

* Military titles
* Academic distinctions

---

# 🔹 Right to Freedom (Articles 19–22)

## Article 19

Provides six freedoms:

* Speech & expression
* Assembly
* Association
* Movement
* Residence
* Profession

📌 Available only to citizens.

---

# 🔵 Reasonable Restrictions

Freedoms are NOT absolute.

Government can impose restrictions for:

* Security
* Public order
* Morality
* Sovereignty

---

# 🔹 Article 20

Protection in criminal cases:

* No ex-post facto law
* No double jeopardy
* No self-incrimination

---

# 🔴 Article 21

### Right to Life & Personal Liberty

Most important FR.

Expanded by Supreme Court to include:

* Privacy
* Clean environment
* Dignity
* Legal aid

📌 “Procedure established by law.”

---

# 🔹 Article 21A

### Right to Education

Children aged:
👉 6–14 years

Added by:

### 86th Amendment

---

# 🔵 Article 22

Protection against arbitrary arrest & detention.

Includes:

* Right to know grounds of arrest
* Consult lawyer
* Produced before magistrate

---

# 🔹 Important Facts

| Article | Right                   |
| ------- | ----------------------- |
| 14      | Equality                |
| 19      | Six freedoms            |
| 21      | Life & liberty          |
| 21A     | Education               |
| 32      | Constitutional remedies |

